| Powerful Supernova May Be Related To Death Spasms of First Stars   |
|   from the we-need-a-few-more-heavy-elements-out-here dept.        |
|   posted by Zonk on Tuesday May 08, @10:43 (Space)                 |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/08/1326231      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

necro81 writes "The New York Times is reporting on a discovery from a
team of UC Berkley researchers, who may have discovered [0]the brightest
stellar explosion ever observed. Observations of [1]the cataclysmic
explosion of a 100- to 200-solar-mass star began last September, based on
data from the Chandra X-ray Observatory. The researchers believe that the
explosion is similar to the death spasms of the first stars in the
universe. The super-massive star's collapse is believed to have been so
energetic as to create [2]unstable electron-positron pairs that tore the
star apart before it could collapse into a black hole — [3]seeding the
universe with heavier elements."

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/08/1326231

