+--------------------------------------------------------------------+
| Own Your Own 128-Bit Integer                                       |
|   from the anyone-can-play dept.                                   |
|   posted by kdawson on Tuesday May 08, @18:32 (Censorship)         |
|   http://science.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/08/2114238      |
+--------------------------------------------------------------------+

[0]Byte Swapper writes "After all the fuss over the AACS [1]trying to
censor a certain 128-bit number that now has something over two million
hits on Google, the folks at Freedom to Tinker would like to point out
that you too can [2]own your own integer. They've set up a script that
will generate a random number, encrypt a copyrighted haiku with it, and
then deed the number back to you. You won't get a copyright on the number
or the haiku, but your number has become an [3]illegal circumvention
device under the DMCA, such that anyone subject to US law caught
distributing it can be punished under the DMCA's anti-trafficking
section, for which the DMCA's Safe Harbor provisions do not apply. So
F9090211749D5BE341D8C5565663C088 is truly mine now, and you can pry it
out of my cold, dead fingers!"

Discuss this story at:
    http://science.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=07/05/08/2114238

Links:
    0. mailto:swap@reversed.com
    1. http://yro.slashdot.org/article.pl?sid=07/05/01/1935250&tid=153
    2. http://www.freedom-to-tinker.com/?p=1155
    3. http://www.eff.org/deeplinks/archives/005229.php



